t7027.text: I can anticipate some of the objections you'll make. It's just a story, presenting an extreme case. Okay, but there's an approximate truth to it. Guys this age all know at least one Jill (usually several) who seems to have everything stacked in her favor in just such a way.

t7028.text: Jack has zero suitors and works at a fast food restaurant for 20 hours a week to pay his bills. He still makes less than Jill. University propaganda reminds him that he's part of an oppressive group (males).

t7029.text: Jill is a progressive girl with few qualms about exploiting her charms. Not only does she have a wide range of suitors to choose from, but she is also paid extravagantly to dance at clubs a few hours on weekends. University propaganda informs her that it's awesome to be a woman.

t7030.text: To consider why that might be, imagine Jack and Jill, both age 18, have just gone off to university. Since women usually date older men, Jill immediately finds a boyfriend amongst the upperclassmen. Jack tries to find a girlfriend, but he's outcompeted by older students.

t7031.text: I think the answer to that is actually yes--especially for young men. They don't necessarily voice it as jealousy, and they don't necessarily want to BE women, but a sense of unfairness motivates some of their anger toward the fairer sex.
